{"questionId":"35034020","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>A king rules a small mountain kingdom which is in the form of a square of length 4 kilometres. The square is described by the co-ordinate system&nbsp;<span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"0 \\leqslant x \\leqslant 4{\\text{,}}\\,\\,0 \\leqslant y \\leqslant 4\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mn>0</mn> <mo>⩽</mo> <mi>x</mi> <mo>⩽</mo> <mn>4</mn> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>0</mn> <mo>⩽</mo> <mi>y</mi> <mo>⩽</mo> <mn>4</mn> </math></span>.</p>\n<p>The king has four&nbsp;adult children,&nbsp;each of which has a luxury palace located at the points <span class=\"mjpage\"><math alttext=\"\\left( {1{\\text{,}}\\,\\,1} \\right){\\text{,}}\\,\\left( {3{\\text{,}}\\,\\,1} \\right){\\text{,}}\\,\\left( {1{\\text{,}}\\,\\,3} \\right){\\text{,}}\\,\\left( {3{\\text{,}}\\,\\,3} \\right)\" xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mrow> <mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mrow> <mtext>,</mtext> </mrow> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mspace width=\"thinmathspace\"></mspace> <mn>3</mn> </mrow> <mo>)</mo> </mrow> </math></span>.&nbsp;Each&nbsp;child owns all the land that is nearer their palace than any other palace.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The king has a fifth (youngest) child who is now just growing up. He installs her in a new palace situated at point (2, 2). The rule about ownership of land is then reapplied.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>State what the shape of the land, owned by the youngest child, is.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>By symmetry a square&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><em><strong>[1 mark]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"35034020","referenceCode":"EXM.2.SL.TZ0.4c","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"State what the shape of the land, owned by the youngest child, is.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"c","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 1]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.6—Voronoi diagrams"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}